      <!-- NZ Privacy Act Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h2>New Zealand Privacy Act 2020</h2>
        
        <div class="definition-box">
          <p>The <strong>Privacy Act 2020</strong> is New Zealand's primary law covering the acquisition, use, storage, and disclosure of personal information. It replaced the Privacy Act of 1993, bringing greater protections, modernised laws, and increased enforcement powers to address the digital age's evolving privacy challenges.</p>
        </div>
        
        <h3>Key Principles Overview</h3>
        <p>The Privacy Act 2020 aims to protect individuals' privacy rights and ensure responsible handling of personal data by organisations.</p>
        
        <div class="key-points">
          <ul>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-shield-alt"></i> <strong>Promote Transparency and Accountability</strong> - Businesses and government entities must be upfront about their data practices.</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-globe"></i> <strong>Align with Global Standards</strong> - Brings New Zealand closer to international frameworks such as the EU's GDPR while preserving local flexibility.</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-gavel"></i> <strong>Improve Enforcement</strong> - Provides the Office of the Privacy Commissioner (OPC) with new compliance and penalty measures.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Global Comparison Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Global Privacy Laws Comparison</h3>
        <p>Key Differences Between GDPR and NZ Privacy Act 2020</p>
        
        <table class="comparison-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Aspect</th>
              <th>GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation, 2016)</th>
              <th>NZ Privacy Act 2020</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Scope</strong></td>
              <td>Applies to all organisations that process EU residents' data, regardless of location.</td>
              <td>Applies to businesses operating in New Zealand and overseas agencies handling NZ data.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Consent</strong></td>
              <td>Explicit consent is essential; must be freely provided, specific, and clear.</td>
              <td>Implied consent may be adequate in certain cases, but must be informed.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Data Subjects Rights</strong></td>
              <td>Right of access, rectification, erasure ("right to be forgotten"), portability, and objection.</td>
              <td>Similar rights, but no explicit "right to be forgotten" - must request erasure under Principle 6.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Penalties</strong></td>
              <td>Up to €20 million or 4% of global turnover (whichever is higher).</td>
              <td>Up to NZ$10,000 for individuals or NZ$1 million for organizations.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Data Breach Notifications</strong></td>
              <td>Must be completed within 72 hours if risk to individuals.</td>
              <td>Mandatory notification if likelihood of serious harm.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>
      
      <!-- Principle 5 Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h2>Principle 5 - Storage and Security of Information</h2>
        
        <div class="definition-box">
          <p>Organisations must ensure there are reasonable safeguards in place to prevent loss, misuse or disclosure of personal information.</p>
        </div>
        
        <p>For serious privacy breaches, organisations must notify the Office of the Privacy Commissioner within 72 hours.</p>
      </section>
      
      <!-- Principle 6 Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Principle 6 – Access to Personal Information</h3>
        <p>Allows individuals to access their personal information held by organizations, enabling them to:</p>
        
        <div class="key-points">
          <ul>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-check-circle"></i> Verify what information is being collected and stored about them</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-check-circle"></i> Understand how their data is being used</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-check-circle"></i> Correct any inaccuracies in their records</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        
        <div class="quote-box">
          <p>This right applies only to the individual's own personal information, not to information about others without explicit consent.</p>
        </div>
      </section>
      
      <!-- Legal Responsibilities Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h3>Legal Responsibilities for Organizations</h3>
        <p>Protocols for managing access requests are outlined in Part 4 subpart 1 of the Privacy Act 2020:</p>
        
        <div class="key-points">
          <ul>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-user"></i> Only the individual concerned can submit an IPP 6 request</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-clock"></i> Agencies must respond within 20 working days</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-exchange-alt"></i> Must transfer requests to appropriate agencies within 10 days if they don't hold the information</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-info-circle"></i> Must provide access instructions if granted</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-ban"></i> Can refuse access for justified reasons</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>
      
      <!-- Retention Requirements Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h2>Retention Requirements</h2>
        
        <div class="two-column-block">
          <!-- Medical Records Column -->
          <div class="column">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-file-medical"></i> Medical Records</h3>
            <div class="definition-box">
              <p>The Health Information Privacy Code requires health agencies to keep medical information only as long as there is a legal purpose.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-points">
              <ul>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-calendar"></i> <strong>10 years</strong> from last service provided (Health (Retention of Health Information) Regulations 1996)</li>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-exclamation"></i> Does not apply if files transferred to patient/executor</li>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-landmark"></i> Public Records Act 2005 specifies retention for public sector health agencies</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <!-- Employee Information Column -->
          <div class="column">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-briefcase"></i> Employee Information</h3>
            <div class="definition-box">
              <p>Retention periods vary based on data type and specific legal requirements.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="key-points">
              <ul>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-clock"></i> Time and wage documentation have specific legal retention periods</li>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-file-invoice-dollar"></i> Tax information has separate requirements</li>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-user-md"></i> Health information (if health services provided) follows medical records rules</li>
                <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-clipboard-list"></i> Employers should maintain clear record-keeping policies</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
      
      <!-- Privacy Rights Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h2>Key Privacy Rights and Obligations</h2>
        
        <div class="definition-box">
          <h3>For Individuals: Know Your Rights</h3>
          <p>In our digital world, understanding privacy rights is crucial as we generate vast amounts of personal data.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="key-points">
          <ul>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-passport"></i> <strong>GDPR</strong>: EU residents can access, correct, delete data, and withdraw consent</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-sun"></i> <strong>CCPA</strong>: Californians can opt-out of data sales and request collection details</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-kiwi-bird"></i> <strong>NZ Privacy Act</strong>: Mandates breach notifications to keep individuals informed</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        
        <div class="definition-box">
          <h3>For Organizations: Compliance Essentials</h3>
          <p>Meeting privacy regulations requires investment but brings significant benefits.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="quote-box">
          <p>"Companies prioritizing transparency build customer trust and brand loyalty, while non-compliance can result in massive fines (up to 4% of global revenue under GDPR) and reputational damage."</p>
        </div>
      </section>
      
      <!-- Case Study Section -->
      <section class="section-block">
        <h2>Case Study: Incomplete Data Removal</h2>
        
        <div class="quote-box">
          <p>A recruitment agency failed to fully remove a former client's profile containing sensitive information (name, photo, qualifications, interests) after receiving a removal request.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="key-points">
          <ul>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Only name and photo were deleted initially</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-search"></i> Remaining information remained accessible via Google search</li>
            <li><i class="fa-icon fas fa-gavel"></i> Violation of Principle 9 (retention) as profile could still identify the individual</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        
        <div class="definition-box">
          <h3>Resolution</h3>
          <p>The agency completely removed the profile after investigation, resolving the complaint satisfactorily.</p>
        </div>
      </section>
